1
00:00:00,320 --> 00:00:11,440
Hello, it's Crawley again. Today we're going to talk about the absolute financial ruin that follows a failing body.

2
00:00:11,440 --> 00:00:16,640
Health insurance is actually a relatively new financial device in the United States.

3
00:00:16,640 --> 00:00:26,080
The earliest contracts weren't issued until the second half of the 19th century, originally designed just to indemnify injuries suffered while traveling in railroad cars.

4
00:00:26,080 --> 00:00:33,760
Later on, these plans expanded to provide 24-hour coverage, including losses arising from general illness.

5
00:00:33,760 --> 00:00:43,120
Today, the basic purpose of health insurance is twofold: to reimburse the cost of medical treatment and to replace lost income in case of illness or injuries.

6
00:00:43,120 --> 00:00:49,920
Imagine a family where the primary wage earner becomes totally disabled from an accident.

7
00:00:49,920 --> 00:00:57,360
He can no longer go to work, the spouse has to stay home, or they must hire someone just to take care of him.

8
00:00:57,360 --> 00:01:06,159
Savings are quickly wiped out, the mortgage is foreclosed, installment purchases are repossessed, and the entire family is reduced to bare subsistence.

9
00:01:06,159 --> 00:01:14,240
To prevent this, policies offer disability income benefits to replace lost earnings. But how do we define disability?

10
00:01:14,240 --> 00:01:23,680
Some policies use a "His Occupation" clause, which is the most liberal definition. Under this, a person is totally disabled if they cannot engage in their regular occupation.

11
00:01:23,680 --> 00:01:34,720
For example, a surgeon who loses their hand in an accident can no longer operate, so they receive benefits even if they are perfectly capable of teaching at a medical college.

12
00:01:34,720 --> 00:01:43,759
Other policies are much stricter, defining disability as the complete inability of the insured to engage in any gainful employment for which they are reasonably fitted.